<subSubSection pageId="777" pageNumber="778" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="777" pageNumber="778">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1920" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Trapezodera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="777" pageNumber="778" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trapezodera</taxonomicName>
Casey, 1920: 19. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1891" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Colpodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="777" pageNumber="778" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aeneicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="777" pageNumber="778">Colpodes aeneicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bates, 1891 by original designation. Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="777" pageNumber="778">trapezion</emphasis>
(an irregular four-shaped figure, by extension trapezoid) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="777" pageNumber="778">dere</emphasis>
(neck, by extension pronotum), alluding to the shape of the pronotum (&quot;trapezoidal outline of the prothorax&quot;) of the adult [feminine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="777" pageNumber="778" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="777" pageNumber="778">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="777" pageNumber="778">Four species are assigned to this subgenus, one from southwestern United States and three from Mexico (Liebherr and Will 1996: 316).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
